<div id="review_2984917555" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2984917555" />
    <a title="Jewel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/808183-jewel"><img alt="Jewel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1601186079p2/808183.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2984917555?book_show_action=true">Sep 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jewel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jewel" href="/user/show/808183-jewel">Jewel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/10224849-a-cook-s-tour">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/808183-jewel?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2984917555" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5611653650618150252">Actual rating: 3.75 stars<br/><br/>For me, the &quot;global adventures&quot; parts of this book were more engaging than the &quot;extreme cuisines&quot;. Don&apos;t get me wrong. I never saw Anthony Bourdain cook, but it&apos;s obvious that the man&apos;s an expert when it came to eating <i>and</i> cooking. I think it&apos;s because I&apos;m more passionate about traveling than cooking/eating that I ended up wavering between excitement and boredom while reading this book. Even though I appreciated Bourdain&apos;s brutally frank and detailed way of describing th</span>
  <span id="freeText5611653650618150252" style="display:none">Actual rating: 3.75 stars<br /><br />For me, the "global adventures" parts of this book were more engaging than the "extreme cuisines". Don't get me wrong. I never saw Anthony Bourdain cook, but it's obvious that the man's an expert when it came to eating <i>and</i> cooking. I think it's because I'm more passionate about traveling than cooking/eating that I ended up wavering between excitement and boredom while reading this book. Even though I appreciated Bourdain's brutally frank and detailed way of describing the extreme cuisines he had tried, I wasn't really amazed enough to think: "Wow, I really have to try this." Instead, most of the time he talked about food I thought: "Okay, can we please move on to the people, scenery, culture, politics, etc.?" Those were the exciting and informative parts that made me, a nerdy picky eater, sit up and pay attention. If I were the note-taking type, I would have filled up a notebook with the travel tips I learned from "A Cook's Tour". <br /><br />There were some food descriptions that did leave a favorable lasting impression. I wanted to try the pho, spring rolls, and iced espresso with condensed milk in Vietnam; fish and chips with malt vinegar in Scotland; and the 20-course meal in The French Laundry in Napa Valley. What do they all have in common? Correct. They are NOT extreme cuisines. I wholeheartedly agree with what Bourdain said (which is also my favorite quote from this book): "Context and memory play powerful roles in all the truly great meals in one's life.” I wish that Bourdain had focused on meals like that instead of extreme cuisines.<br /><br />As I mentioned above, I liked Bourdain's honesty and his lack of pretensions. However, he made crass comments that were off-putting and unnecessary. I'm not even going to cite examples because reading them once already made me cringe. For those of you who are wondering, those comments involved women's body parts. <br /><br />Lastly, I admired Bourdain for his sense of adventure and willingness to learn as he immersed himself in different cultures. I believe that's what made him a really good travel writer. He interacted with people from all walks of life and it's not the shallow type of interaction. He took the time and made the effort to have meaningful interactions with them and in return, they enriched his traveling experience by providing him with a wealth of knowledge, which he did not take for granted.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5611653650618150252" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

